'''Michael Stanley Dukakis''' ({{IPAc-en|d|ʉ|ˈ|k|ɑː|k|ɨ|s}}; born November 3, 1933) served as the 65th and 67th Governor of [[Massachusetts]], from 1975 to 1979 and 1983 to 1991 respectively. He is the longest-serving Governor in Massachusetts history and only the second [[Greek American]] Governor in U.S. history, after [[Spiro Agnew]]. In 1988, he was the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[United States presidential election, 1988|nominee for President]], but lost to the  [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate, then–[[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]], [[George H. W. Bush]].

==Early life and education==
Dukakis's father Panos (1896&ndash;1979) was a Greek immigrant from [[Edremit (District), Balıkesir|Adramyttion (Edremit)]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=mcTvNg77kp4C&pg=PA176&lpg=PA176&dq=%22Edremit%22+%2B+%22panos+dukakis%22&source=bl&ots=f8Nc_ys9q5&sig=HV-2HHLLpssqDiSxR9BcrVCd9Us&hl=en&ei=OuSjSZP_IpKWsQOm4cyzAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=5&ct=result|title= Greek Americans: Struggle and Success|edition=2nd|author=Charles C. Moskos|page=176|publisher=Transaction Publishers|date=1989|isbn=0-88738-778-0|accessdate=2015-04-05}}</ref> in [[Turkey]], which was then the [[Ottoman Empire]], who settled in [[Lowell, Massachusetts]] in 1912, and graduated from [[Harvard Medical School]] twelve years later, subsequently working as an [[Obstetrics|obstetrician]]. Dukakis' mother Euterpe (née Boukis; 1903–2003) was a [[Vlachs|Vlach]]-[[Aromanians|Aromanian]] immigrant from [[Larissa]], in [[Thessaly]], [[northern Greece]];<ref name=NYT>{{cite news | url=http://www.nytimes.com/1988/10/17/us/campaign-trail-tapping-another-ethnic-group.html | author=Bernard Weinraub | title=Campaign Trail; Tapping Another Ethnic Group | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=October 17, 1988 | accessdate=August 24, 2008}}</ref> she and her family emigrated to [[Haverhill, Massachusetts]], in 1913.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/news/daily/03/dukakis.htm|title=Euterpe Dukakis, mother of former Mass. governor, dies at 99 |agency=Associated Press |date=April 3, 2003 |publisher=''The Boston Globe''}}</ref>

Dukakis attended [[Brookline High School]] in his hometown,<ref>[http://www.nytimes.com/1988/07/23/opinion/fanfares-for-michael-dukakis.html "Fanfares for Michael Dukakis"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', July 23, 1988. Retrieved February 5, 2008. "And then the candidate, once a trumpeter in the Brookline High School band, took the podium and performed his own Fanfare for the Common Man."</ref> where he was an honor student and a member of the basketball, baseball, tennis, and cross-country teams.<ref>{{Cite book | last=Ruttman | first=Larry | year= 2005 | url=http://www.voicesofbrookline.com | title=Voices of Brookline | publisher=Peter E. Randall Publisher LLC | location=Portsmouth, New Hampshire | page=195 | isbn=1-931807-39-6 | accessdate=December 30, 2013}}</ref> He graduated from [[Swarthmore College]] in 1955, served in the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] 1955–1957, stationed in [[Korea]], and then received his [[Juris Doctor|law degree]] from [[Harvard Law School]] in 1960. Dukakis is also an [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scout]] and recipient of the [[Distinguished Eagle Scout Award]] from the [[Boy Scouts of America]].<ref name="honor">{{Cite book | last=Townley | first=Alvin | origyear= December 26, 2006 | url=http://www.thomasdunnebooks.com/TD_TitleDetail.aspx?ISBN=0312366531 | title=Legacy of Honor: The Values and Influence of America's Eagle Scouts | publisher=St. Martin's Press | location=New York | pages=192–196 | isbn=0-312-36653-1 | accessdate=December 29, 2006}}</ref> Dukakis began his political career as an elected Town Meeting Member in the town of Brookline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northeastern.edu/dukakiscenter/about/kitty-and-michael-dukakis-biographies/ |title=Kitty and Michael Dukakis Biographies |publisher=Northeastern.edu |date= |accessdate=2015-04-05}}</ref>

==Massachusetts governor==
===First governorship (1975–1979)===
{{Main|Massachusetts gubernatorial election, 1974}}
After serving four terms in the [[Massachusetts House of Representatives]] between 1962 and 1970 (and winning the Democratic nomination for lieutenant governor in 1970<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hri.org/hri/dukakis.html |title=Michael S. Dukakis |publisher=Hri.org |date=1933-11-03 |accessdate=2015-04-05}}</ref>), Dukakis was elected governor in 1974, defeating the incumbent Republican [[Francis Sargent]] during a period of fiscal crisis. Dukakis won in part by promising to be a "reformer" and pledging a "lead pipe guarantee" of no new taxes to balance the state budget. He would later reverse his position after taking office. He also pledged to dismantle the powerful [[Department of Conservation and Recreation (Massachusetts)|Metropolitan District Commission]] (MDC), a bureaucratic enclave that served as home to hundreds of political patronage employees. The MDC managed state parks, reservoirs, and waterways, as well as the highways and roads abutting those waterways. In addition to its own police force, the MDC had its own maritime patrol force, and an enormous budget from the state, for which it provided minimal accounting. Dukakis' efforts to dismantle the MDC failed in the legislature, where the MDC had many powerful supporters. As a result, the MDC would withhold its critical backing of Dukakis in the 1978 gubernatorial primary.

Governor Dukakis hosted [[Gerald Ford|President Ford]] and [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Britain's Queen Elizabeth II]] during their visits to Boston in 1976 to commemorate the [[United States Bicentennial|bicentennial of the United States]].{{citation needed|date=November 2013}} He gained some notice as the only politician in the state government who went to work during the [[Northeastern United States blizzard of 1978|Blizzard of 1978]], during which he went to local TV studios in a sweater to announce emergency bulletins.<ref>{{Cite news| url = http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2008/02/03/have_we_learned_anything/?page=full |title= Have we learned anything?|author= Peter J. Howe |publisher=The Boston Globe |date =February 3, 2008}}</ref> Dukakis is also remembered for his 1977 [[exoneration]] of [[Sacco and Vanzetti]], two Italian anarchists whose trial sparked protests around the world.

During his first term in office, Dukakis [[Commutation of sentence|commuted the sentences]] of 21 first-degree murderers and 23 second-degree murderers. Due to controversy engendered by some of these individuals having re-offended, Dukakis curtailed the practice later, issuing no commutations in his last three years as governor.<ref>{{Cite news | title=If you thought Duke's commutations were bad, be warned: Patrick's could be so much worse | url=http://news.bostonherald.com/columnists/view.bg?articleid=160964 | work=[[Boston Herald]] |publisher= |first=Howie |last=Carr | date=October 6, 2006 | accessdate=September 9, 2013}}</ref>

However, his first term performance proved to be insufficient to offset a backlash against the state's high sales and property tax rates, which turned out to be the predominant issue in the 1978 gubernatorial campaign. Dukakis, despite being the incumbent Democratic governor, was refused renomination by his own party. The [[Massachusetts Democratic Party|state's Democratic Party]] chose to support Director of the [[Massachusetts Port Authority]] [[Edward J. King]] in the [[primary election|primary]], partly because King rode the wave against high property taxes, but more significantly because state Democratic Party leaders lost confidence in Dukakis' ability to govern effectively. King also enjoyed the support of the power brokers at the MDC, who were unhappy with Dukakis' attempts to dismantle their powerful bureaucracy. King also had support from state police and public employee unions. Dukakis suffered a scathing defeat in the primary, a disappointment that his wife Kitty called "a public death".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/print/1988-01-17/news/mn-36772_1_michael-dukakis|title=An Enigma: For Dukakis, Key Is Voter Perception|date=January 17, 1988|first=Bob|last=Drogin|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref>

